{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614076"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16339"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9030"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116457"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9030"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98456"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"7517"},{"type":"tags","id":"7518"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21485"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116457"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe choroid of the eye consists of multiple layers that serve different functions. One layer forms a specialised interface between the sclera and the main choroidal stroma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the layer of the choroid that forms a mobile interface between the sclera and choroidal stroma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bruch\u0027s membrane","Choriocapillaris","Lamina fusca","Haller\u0027s layer","Sattler\u0027s layer"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elamina fusca\u003C/strong\u003E is the outermost layer of the choroid that forms a transitional zone between the sclera and choroidal stroma. It contains elastic fibres and allows for movement between these layers during eye movement and accommodation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBruch\u0027s membrane\u003C/strong\u003E is the innermost layer that separates the choroid from the retinal pigment epithelium. The \u003Cstrong\u003Echoriocapillaris\u003C/strong\u003E is a dense network of capillaries that provides oxygen and nutrients to the outer retina. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaller\u0027s layer\u003C/strong\u003E contains large blood vessels while \u003Cstrong\u003ESattler\u0027s layer\u003C/strong\u003E contains medium-sized blood vessels. These layers work together to support the metabolic needs of the outer retina while maintaining the structural integrity of the eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The choroid has five distinct layers from outer to inner: lamina fusca, Haller\u0027s layer, Sattler\u0027s layer, choriocapillaris, and Bruch\u0027s membrane.","The lamina fusca is a transitional layer between sclera and choroid that contains elastic fibres allowing for movement between these layers."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","i